2026-06-17 | Find K-th Character in Final Processed String

	Question
Return the character at index k in the final string, or '.' if k is outside the final string.
	Key Insight
Building the entire string may be impossible because:
		"#"
		doubles the size.
Instead:
1.	Compute the length after every operation.
2.	Walk backwards through the operations.
3.	Map the required index k to the corresponding index in the previous state.
This is similar to decoding an encoded string.
	Reverse Mapping Rules
Let len be the current length.
Letter c:
		previous length = len - 1
		if k == len - 1
				answer = c
		else
				continue
'*':
		deletion removed one character.
		Going backwards:
		length increases by 1.
		k remains unchanged.
'#':
		current string = old + old
		length = 2 * oldLength
		if k >= oldLength
				k -= oldLength
'%':
		current string = reverse(old)
		k = oldLength - 1 - k
	Approach
1.	Compute length after each operation.
2.	If k is outside final length:
		return '.'
3.	Process operations from right to left.
4.	Continuously transform k into the corresponding index in the previous state.
5.	When a letter creates the required position,
		return that letter.
	Time Complexity
	O(n)
	Space Complexity
	O(n)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    char kthCharacter(string s, long long k) {
        int n = s.size();
        vector<long long> len(n + 1, 0);
        for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            char ch = s[i];
            if(ch >= 'a' && ch <= 'z') {
                len[i + 1] = len[i] + 1;
            }
            else if(ch == '*') {
                len[i + 1] = max(0LL, len[i] - 1);
            }
            else if(ch == '#') {
                len[i + 1] = min((long long)4e18,
                                 len[i] * 2);
            }
            else { // %
                len[i + 1] = len[i];
            }
        }
        if(k >= len[n])
            return '.';
        for(int i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
            char ch = s[i];
            if(ch >= 'a' && ch <= 'z') {
                if(k == len[i])
                    return ch;
            }
            else if(ch == '#') {
                long long oldLen = len[i];
                if(k >= oldLen)
                    k -= oldLen;
            }
            else if(ch == '%') {
                long long oldLen = len[i];
                k = oldLen - 1 - k;
            }
            else { // '*'
                // length before deletion = len[i]
                // after deletion = len[i+1]
                // surviving indices stay unchanged
            }
        }
        return '.';
    }
};
	Key Insight
Instead of constructing the exponentially growing string, track only its length and work backwards. Each operation provides a simple mapping from an index in the current string to the corresponding index in the previous string, allowing the k-th character to be found in O(n) time.
